name: DigitalHistory_
tweet: Splash Mountain riders assume the identity of Br‚Äôer Rabbit, a leporid trickster runaway trying to outwit violent capturers in the South‚Äôs swamplands. He's a fugitive slave. Along the way, Rabbit, stops to satisfy his gastronomical proclivities as he outsmarts his violent pursuers

name: DigitalHistory_
tweet: The ‚Äúcarefree time‚Äù it attempted to resurrect from the past (the height of Jim Crow America) was a white 1955 phantasmal interpretation of Americana that was racially exclusive in its erasure of both past diversity and violence. 1955 was the same year as Montgomery Bus Boycotts.

name: DigitalHistory_
tweet: Disneyland‚Äôs Main Street U.S.A. opened 1955 & was supposed to resemble Marceline, Missouri (Walt Disney‚Äôs hometown), circa 1910, as the epitome of old-time American culture. Disney dedicated it ‚ÄúFor those of us who remember the carefree time it recreates."

name: DigitalHistory_
tweet: A haunted plantation overlooks the Rivers of America (a stand-in for the Mississippi & Missouri Rivers). Interestingly, this is the only part of the park for decades that played non-Disney music. Primarily Dixieland jazz and instrumental Stephen Foster music (blackface classics).

name: DigitalHistory_
tweet: The thing I find most striking about Song of the South's representation in Splash Mountain at Disneyland is its geography--in between New Orleans Square, Critter Country, & Tom Sawyer's Island. African American history & slavery is represented by ghosts & animals.
